Can Islam French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when the Swiss voters have voted for a ban on building minarets and the concern about the alleged Islamisation of Europe, John Bowen, an American academic, wrote a thorough and thoughtful report on whether Muslims can be integrated into one of the avowedly säkularisiertesten societies of Europe and be integrated.
Some readers will this new book from admiration for the work of the author: " Why do the French no love " (original title: " Why the French Don't Like Headscarves ") (2006) , an elegant and densely argumentierenden study of a contentious issue, which the country about one and a half decades and employed and whose effects are still visible.
Bowens neustes book offers a more comprehensive and kühneres spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he would like to know not only what the politicians and the media about Islam in France, but what is happening on the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes, now the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls " Islamic space ".
He is a good listener, he gives debates between teachers and students, on the issues that concern them most.
Should a Muslim in a mosque or a City hall (or both) ?
Should be lectured young Muslims about evolution and rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marrying a non - Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim, to use an interest - oriented banking system in order to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly mundane matters, he claims, the daily life, in contrast to the political drama, the media.
The author acknowledges a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a familiar name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, a Swiss - born Arab - Muslim scholars and academics.
This new generation is trying to open the debate about how it is possible, on the one hand, a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society.
They do not have all the arguments on their side.
The conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists interviewed Bowen, are with their Salafi counterparts usually divided - supporters of the puristischen Sunni Islam, with Saudi Arabia - which is a small but influential presence show among Europe's Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But a convention requires a give and take on both sides.
He queries whether the French political decision - makers (and the intellectual elite, so passionate the separation of church and state) really committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may be a rougher treatment than Catholics, Protestants and Jews, who had to make their historic compromise with the secular Republicanism.
He sees a " tightening of the values " as a growing pragmatism.
Islam can be French? After reading this book, one is tempted to say " yes, but not yet. "
