The proposal would offer the opportunity, with a speed of 400 km/h, which the British rail network would be the quickest of Europe.
The first route was planned that 400 metres long trains with a maximum capacity of 1,100 people can travel to.
Up to 18 trains per hour on the London - Birmingham in operation.
This in turn would mean that a terminus in London, would be on the 20,000 passengers per hour could be dealt.
Given the space limitations in the capital, it is expected that an existing station would be extended to the high - speed network.
Rail experts say that only St Pancras International or Euston this potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not this plan, in his opinion, should be continued, but the lengthy public consultation and planning measures mean that a final decision will be taken until after the parliamentary elections.
But even if he sets the wheels in motion, the rail network to be built in sections.
The trains would have to switch from the high - speed lines to existing rail lines in the north of Birmingham, and the journey time between London and Scotland in about three hours.
This is seen as a key sticking point, so that a switch from air to rail can be a beacon for the rail revolution.
